# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lagrangian-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In physics, **action** is a scalar quantity that describes how the balance of kinetic versus potential energy of a physical system changes with trajectory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Action is significant because it is an input to the principle of stationary action, an approach to classical mechanics that is simpler for multiple objects.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Action and the variational principle are used in Feynman's formulation of quantum mechanics and in general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For systems with small values of action close to the Planck constant, quantum effects are significant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] More formally, action is a mathematical functional which takes the trajectory (also called path or history) of the system as its argument and has a real number as its result.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Generally, the action takes different values for different paths.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Action has dimensions of energy × time or momentum × length, and its SI unit is joule-second (like the Planck constant h).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Introductory physics often begins with Newton's laws of motion, relating force and motion; action is part of a completely equivalent alternative approach with practical and educational advantages.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] However, the concept took many decades to supplant Newtonian approaches and remains a challenge to introduce to students.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The kinetic energy of a ball of mass m is ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2 where v is the velocity of the ball; the potential energy is mgx where g is the acceleration due to gravity and x its height.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] This makes the action an input to the powerful stationary-action principle for classical and for quantum mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Newton's equations of motion for the ball can be derived from the action using the stationary-action principle, but the advantages of action-based mechanics only begin to appear in cases where Newton's laws are difficult to apply.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Replace the ball with an electron: classical mechanics fails but stationary action continues to work.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The energy difference in the simple action definition, kinetic minus potential energy, is generalized and called the Lagrangian for more complex cases.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The Planck constant, written as h, is the quantum (the minimal possible amount) of action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] It is related to the quantum of angular momentum, ħ, by the relation *ħ* = ⁠*h*/2*π*⁠.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] These constants have units of energy times time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] They appear in all significant quantum equations, such as the uncertainty principle and the de Broglie wavelength.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Whenever the value of the action approaches the Planck constant, quantum effects are significant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Pierre Louis Maupertuis and Leonhard Euler working in the 1740s developed early versions of the action principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Joseph Louis Lagrange clarified the mathematics when he invented the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] William Rowan Hamilton made the next big breakthrough, formulating Hamilton's principle in 1853.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Hamilton's principle became the cornerstone for classical work with different forms of action until Richard Feynman and Julian Schwinger developed quantum action principles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Expressed in mathematical language, using the calculus of variations, the evolution of a physical system (that is, how the system actually progresses from one state to another) corresponds to a stationary point (usually, a minimum) of the action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Action has the dimensions of [energy] × [time], and its SI unit is joule-second, which is identical to the unit of angular momentum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Several different definitions of "the action" are in common use in physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The action is usually an integral over time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] However, when the action pertains to fields, it may be integrated over spatial variables as well.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In some cases, the action is integrated along the path followed by the physical system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The action is typically represented as an integral over time, taken along the path of the system between the initial time and the final time of the development of the system: ${\mathcal {S}}=\int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}L\,dt,$ where the integrand L is called the Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For the action integral to be well-defined, the trajectory has to be bounded in time and space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Most commonly, the term is used for a functional 𝒮 which takes a function of time and (for fields) space as input and returns a scalar.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In classical mechanics, the input function is the evolution **q**(*t*) of the system between times *t*1 and *t*2, where **q** represents the generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] According to Hamilton's principle, the true evolution **q**true(*t*) is an evolution for which the action 𝒮[**q**(*t*)] is stationary (a minimum, maximum, or a saddle point).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] This principle results in the equations of motion in Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In addition to the action functional, there is another functional called the *abbreviated action*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In the abbreviated action, the input function is the *path* followed by the physical system without regard to its parameterization by time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For example, the path of a planetary orbit is an ellipse, and the path of a particle in a uniform gravitational field is a parabola; in both cases, the path does not depend on how fast the particle traverses the path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] According to Maupertuis's principle, the true path of the system is a path for which the abbreviated action is stationary.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] When the total energy E is conserved, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation can be solved with the additive separation of variables: $S(q_{1},\dots ,q_{N},t)=W(q_{1},\dots ,q_{N})-E\cdot t,$ where the time-independent function *W*(*q*1,*q*2,…,*qN*) is called *Hamilton's characteristic function*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The corresponding canonical variable conjugate to *Jk* is its "angle" *wk*, for reasons described more fully under action-angle coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The integration is only over a single variable *qk* and, therefore, unlike the integrated dot product in the abbreviated action integral above.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The *Jk* variable equals the change in *Sk*(*qk*) as *qk* is varied around the closed path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For several physical systems of interest, *Jk* is either a constant or varies very slowly; hence, the variable *Jk* is often used in perturbation calculations and in determining adiabatic invariants.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For example, they are used in the calculation of planetary and satellite orbits.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Physical laws are frequently expressed as differential equations, which describe how physical quantities such as position and momentum change continuously with time, space or a generalization thereof.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Given the initial and boundary conditions for the situation, the "solution" to these empirical equations is one or more functions that describe the behavior of the system and are called *equations of motion*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The action principle provides deep insights into physics, and is an important concept in modern theoretical physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Various action principles and related concepts are summarized below.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In classical mechanics, Maupertuis's principle (named after Pierre Louis Maupertuis) states that the path followed by a physical system is the one of least length (with a suitable interpretation of path and length).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Maupertuis's principle uses the abbreviated action between two generalized points on a path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Hamilton's principle states that the differential equations of motion for *any* physical system can be re-formulated as an equivalent integral equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Thus, there are two distinct approaches for formulating dynamical models.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Hamilton's principle applies not only to the classical mechanics of a single particle, but also to classical fields such as the electromagnetic and gravitational fields.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Hamilton's principal function *S* = *S*(*q*,*t*;*q*0,*t*0) is obtained from the action functional 𝒮 by fixing the initial time *t*0 and the initial endpoint *q*0, while allowing the upper time limit t and the second endpoint q to vary.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The Hamilton's principal function satisfies the Hamilton–Jacobi equation, a formulation of classical mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Due to a similarity with the Schrödinger equation, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation provides, arguably, the most direct link with quantum mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In Lagrangian mechanics, the requirement that the action integral be stationary under small perturbations is equivalent to a set of differential equations (called the Euler–Lagrange equations) that may be obtained using the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The **action principle** can be extended to obtain the equations of motion for fields, such as the electromagnetic field or gravitational field.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Maxwell's equations can be derived as conditions of stationary action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The Einstein equation utilizes the *Einstein–Hilbert action* as constrained by a variational principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The trajectory (path in spacetime) of a body in a gravitational field can be found using the action principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For a free falling body, this trajectory is a geodesic.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Implications of symmetries in a physical situation can be found with the action principle, together with the Euler–Lagrange equations, which are derived from the action principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] An example is Noether's theorem, which states that to every continuous symmetry in a physical situation there corresponds a conservation law (and conversely).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] This deep connection requires that the action principle be assumed.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] In quantum mechanics, the system does not follow a single path whose action is stationary, but the behavior of the system depends on all permitted paths and the value of their action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The action corresponding to the various paths is used to calculate the path integral, which gives the probability amplitudes of the various outcomes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Although equivalent in classical mechanics with Newton's laws, the **action principle** is better suited for generalizations and plays an important role in modern physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] Indeed, this principle is one of the great generalizations in physical science.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] It is best understood within quantum mechanics, particularly in Richard Feynman's path integral formulation, where it arises out of destructive interference of quantum amplitudes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The action principle can be generalized still further.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] For example, the action need not be an integral, because nonlocal actions are possible.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] The configuration space need not even be a functional space, given certain features such as noncommutative geometry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/action-physics] However, a physical basis for these mathematical extensions remains to be established experimentally.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The **calculus of variations** (or **variational calculus**) is a field of mathematical analysis that uses variations, which are small changes in functions and functionals, to find maxima and minima of functionals: mappings from a set of functions to the real numbers.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Functionals are often expressed as definite integrals involving functions and their derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Functions that maximize or minimize functionals may be found using the Euler–Lagrange equation of the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] A simple example of such a problem is to find the curve of shortest length connecting two points.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] If there are no constraints, the solution is a straight line between the points.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] However, if the curve is constrained to lie on a surface in space, then the solution is less obvious, and possibly many solutions may exist.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Such solutions are known as *geodesics*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] A related problem is posed by Fermat's principle: light follows the path of shortest optical length connecting two points, which depends upon the material of the medium.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] One corresponding concept in mechanics is the principle of least/stationary action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Many important problems involve functions of several variables.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Solutions of boundary value problems for the Laplace equation satisfy the Dirichlet's principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Plateau's problem requires finding a surface of minimal area that spans a given contour in space: a solution can often be found by dipping a frame in soapy water.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Although such experiments are relatively easy to perform, their mathematical formulation is far from simple: there may be more than one locally minimizing surface, and they may have non-trivial topology.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This problem was followed by the brachistochrone curve problem raised by Johann Bernoulli (1696), which was similar to one raised by Galileo Galilei in 1638, but he did not solve the problem explicitly nor did he use the methods based on calculus.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Bernoulli solved the problem using the principle of least time in the process, but not calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] In 1697 Newton solved the problem using variational techniques, and as a result, he pioneered the field with his work on the two problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The problem would immediately occupy the attention of Jacob Bernoulli and the Marquis de l'Hôpital, but Leonhard Euler first elaborated the subject, beginning in 1733.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Joseph-Louis Lagrange was influenced by Euler's work to contribute greatly to the theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] After Euler saw the 1755 work of the 19-year-old Lagrange, Euler dropped his own partly geometric approach in favor of Lagrange's purely analytic approach and renamed the subject the *calculus of variations* in his 1756 lecture *Elementa Calculi Variationum*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Adrien-Marie Legendre (1786) laid down a method, not entirely satisfactory, for the discrimination of maxima and minima.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Isaac Newton and Gottfried Leibniz also gave some early attention to the subject.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] To this discrimination Vincenzo Brunacci (1810), Carl Friedrich Gauss (1829), Siméon Poisson (1831), Mikhail Ostrogradsky (1834), and Carl Jacobi (1837) have been among the contributors.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] An important general work is that of Pierre Frédéric Sarrus (1842) which was condensed and improved by Augustin-Louis Cauchy (1844).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Other valuable treatises and memoirs have been written by Strauch (1849), John Hewitt Jellett (1850), Otto Hesse (1857), Alfred Clebsch (1858), and Lewis Buffett Carll (1885), but perhaps the most important work of the century is that of Karl Weierstrass.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] His celebrated course on the theory is epoch-making, and it may be asserted that he was the first to place it on a firm and unquestionable foundation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The 20th and the 23rd Hilbert problem published in 1900 encouraged further development.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] In the 20th century David Hilbert, Oskar Bolza, Gilbert Ames Bliss, Emmy Noether, Leonida Tonelli, Henri Lebesgue and Jacques Hadamard among others made significant contributions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Marston Morse applied calculus of variations in what is now called Morse theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Lev Pontryagin, Ralph Rockafellar and F.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Clarke developed new mathematical tools for the calculus of variations in optimal control theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The dynamic programming of Richard Bellman is an alternative to the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The calculus of variations is concerned with the maxima or minima (collectively called **extrema**) of functionals.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] A functional maps functions to scalars, so functionals have been described as "functions of functions." Functionals have extrema with respect to the elements y of a given function space defined over a given domain.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] A functional $J[y]$ is said to have an extremum at the function f if $\Delta J=J[y]-J[f]$ has the same sign for all y in an arbitrarily small neighborhood of $f.$ The function f is called an **extremal** function or extremal.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The extremum $J[f]$ is called a local maximum if $\Delta J\leq 0$ everywhere in an arbitrarily small neighborhood of $f,$ and a local minimum if $\Delta J\geq 0$ there.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] For a function space of continuous functions, extrema of corresponding functionals are called **strong extrema** or **weak extrema**, depending on whether the first derivatives of the continuous functions are respectively all continuous or not.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Both strong and weak extrema of functionals are for a space of continuous functions but strong extrema have the additional requirement that the first derivatives of the functions in the space be continuous.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Thus a strong extremum is also a weak extremum, but the converse may not hold.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Finding strong extrema is more difficult than finding weak extrema.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] An example of a necessary condition that is used for finding weak extrema is the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Finding the extrema of functionals is similar to finding the maxima and minima of functions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The maxima and minima of a function may be located by finding the points where its derivative vanishes (i.e., is equal to zero).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The extrema of functionals may be obtained by finding functions for which the functional derivative is equal to zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This leads to solving the associated Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] where $L\left[x,y,y'\right]\to L\left[x,f,f'\right]$ when $\varepsilon =0$ and we have used integration by parts on the second term.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The second term on the second line vanishes because $\eta =0$ at $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ by definition.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] According to the fundamental lemma of calculus of variations, the fact that this equation holds for any choice of $\eta$ implies that the part of the integrand in parentheses is zero, i.e.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] which is called the **Euler–Lagrange equation**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Note that assuming y is a function of x loses generality; ideally both should be a function of some other parameter.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This approach is good solely for instructive purposes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] and we have thus found the extremal function $f(x)$ that minimizes the functional $A[y]$ so that $A[f]$ is a minimum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The equation for a straight line is $y=mx+b.$ In other words, the shortest distance between two points is a straight line.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] In physics problems it may be the case that ${\frac {\partial L}{\partial x}}=0,$ meaning the integrand is a function of $f(x)$ and $f'(x)$ but x does not appear separately.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The intuition behind this result is that, if the variable x is actually time, then the statement ${\frac {\partial L}{\partial x}}=0$ implies that the Lagrangian is time-independent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] By Noether's theorem, there is an associated conserved quantity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] In this case, this quantity is the Hamiltonian, the Legendre transform of the Lagrangian, which (often) coincides with the energy of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This is (minus) the constant in Beltrami's identity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Recently, methods have been developed to incorporate symmetry information directly into the inverse problem of the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] By combining the Helmholtz conditions involved in the inverse problem with relations derived from Noether's identity, it is possible to reconstruct Lagrangians that reproduce given equations of motion while ensuring the presence of prescribed symmetries.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The discussion thus far has assumed that extremal functions possess two continuous derivatives, although the existence of the integral J requires only first derivatives of trial functions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The condition that the first variation vanishes at an extremal may be regarded as a **weak form** of the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The theorem of Du Bois-Reymond asserts that this weak form implies the strong form.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] then f has two continuous derivatives, and it satisfies the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Hilbert was the first to give good conditions for the Euler–Lagrange equations to give a stationary solution.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Within a convex area and a positive thrice differentiable Lagrangian the solutions are composed of a countable collection of sections that either go along the boundary or satisfy the Euler–Lagrange equations in the interior.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] However Lavrentiev in 1926 showed that there are circumstances where there is no optimum solution but one can be approached arbitrarily closely by increasing numbers of sections.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The Lavrentiev Phenomenon identifies a difference in the infimum of a minimization problem across different classes of admissible functions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Clearly, $x(t)=t^{\frac {1}{3}}$ minimizes the functional, but we find any function $x\in W^{1,\infty }$ gives a value bounded away from the infimum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Connected with the Lavrentiev Phenomenon is the repulsion property: any functional displaying Lavrentiev's Phenomenon will display the weak repulsion property.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Plateau's problem consists of finding a function that minimizes the surface area while assuming prescribed values on the boundary of D ; the solutions are called **minimal surfaces**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The functional V is to be minimized among all trial functions $\varphi$ that assume prescribed values on the boundary of D .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] for all smooth functions v that vanish on the boundary of D .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The difficulty with this reasoning is the assumption that the minimizing function u must have two derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Riemann argued that the existence of a smooth minimizing function was assured by the connection with the physical problem: membranes do indeed assume configurations with minimal potential energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Riemann named this idea the Dirichlet principle in honor of his teacher Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] among all functions $\varphi$ that satisfy $\varphi (-1)=-1$ and $\varphi (1)=1.$ W can be made arbitrarily small by choosing piecewise linear functions that make a transition between −1 and 1 in a small neighborhood of the origin.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] However, there is no function that makes $W=0.$ Eventually it was shown that Dirichlet's principle is valid, but it requires a sophisticated application of the regularity theory for elliptic partial differential equations; see Jost and Li–Jost (1998).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This corresponds to an external force density $f(x,y)$ in $D,$ an external force $g(s)$ on the boundary $C,$ and elastic forces with modulus $\sigma (s)$ acting on C .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The function that minimizes the potential energy **with no restriction on its boundary values** will be denoted by u .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Provided that f and g are continuous, regularity theory implies that the minimizing function u will have two derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] In taking the first variation, no boundary condition need be imposed on the increment v .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This boundary condition is a consequence of the minimizing property of u : it is not imposed beforehand.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Such conditions are called **natural boundary conditions**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The preceding reasoning is not valid if $\sigma$ vanishes identically on $C.$ In such a case, we could allow a trial function $\varphi \equiv c$ , where c is a constant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] By appropriate choice of c , V can assume any value unless the quantity inside the brackets vanishes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This condition implies that net external forces on the system are in equilibrium.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] If these forces are in equilibrium, then the variational problem has a solution, but it is not unique, since an arbitrary constant may be added.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Further details and examples are in Courant and Hilbert (1953).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Both one-dimensional and multi-dimensional **eigenvalue problems** can be formulated as variational problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The functions $p(x)$ and $r(x)$ are required to be everywhere positive and bounded away from zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The primary variational problem is to minimize the ratio $Q/R$ among all y satisfying the endpoint conditions, which is equivalent to minimizing $Q[y]$ under the constraint that $R[y]$ is constant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] It can be shown (see Gelfand and Fomin 1963) that the minimizing u has two derivatives and satisfies the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The associated $\lambda$ will be denoted by $\lambda _{1}$ ; it is the lowest eigenvalue for this equation and boundary conditions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The associated minimizing function will be denoted by $u_{1}(x)$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This variational characterization of eigenvalues leads to the Rayleigh–Ritz method: choose an approximating u as a linear combination of basis functions (for example trigonometric functions) and carry out a finite-dimensional minimization among such linear combinations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This method is often surprisingly accurate.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] This procedure can be extended to obtain the complete sequence of eigenvalues and eigenfunctions for the problem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] The variational problem also applies to more general boundary conditions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] where $\lambda$ is given by the ratio $Q[u]/R[u]$ as previously.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] These latter conditions are the **natural boundary conditions** for this problem, since they are not imposed on trial functions for the minimization, but are instead a consequence of the minimization.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/calculus-of-variations] Eigenvalue problems in higher dimensions are defined in analogy with the one-dimensional case.
