[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] D'Alembert's principle can be applied in cases of kinematic constraints that depend on velocities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The principle does not apply for irreversible displacements, such as sliding friction, and more general specification of the irreversibility is required.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The principle states that the sum of the differences between the forces acting on a system of massive particles and the time derivatives of the momenta of the system itself projected onto any virtual displacement consistent with the constraints of the system is zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Newton's dot notation is used to represent the derivative with respect to time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The above equation is often called d'Alembert's principle, but it was first written in this variational form by Joseph Louis Lagrange.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] D'Alembert's contribution was to demonstrate that in the totality of a dynamic system the forces of constraint vanish.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] That is to say that the generalized forces $\mathbf {Q} _{j}$ need not include constraint forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] It is equivalent to the somewhat more cumbersome Gauss's principle of least constraint.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The general statement of d'Alembert's principle mentions "the time derivatives of the momenta of the system." By Newton's second law, the first time derivative of momentum is the force.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Consider Newton's law for a system of particles of constant mass, i .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Considering the virtual work, $\delta W$ , done by the total and inertial forces together through an arbitrary virtual displacement, $\delta \mathbf {r} _{i}$ , of the system leads to a zero identity, since the forces involved sum to zero for each particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The original vector equation could be recovered by recognizing that the work expression must hold for arbitrary displacements.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Such displacements are said to be *consistent* with the constraints.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] There is also a corresponding principle for static systems called the principle of virtual work for applied forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] D'Alembert showed that one can transform an accelerating rigid body into an equivalent static system by adding the so-called "inertial force" and "inertial torque" or moment.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The inertial force must act through the center of mass and the inertial torque can act anywhere.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The system can then be analyzed exactly as a static system subjected to this "inertial force and moment" and the external forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] The advantage is that in the equivalent static system one can take moments about any point (not just the center of mass).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] This often leads to simpler calculations because any force (in turn) can be eliminated from the moment equations by choosing the appropriate point about which to apply the moment equation (sum of moments = zero).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Even in the course of Fundamentals of Dynamics and Kinematics of machines, this principle helps in analyzing the forces that act on a link of a mechanism when it is in motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] In textbooks of engineering dynamics, this is sometimes referred to as *d'Alembert's principle*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Some educators caution that attempts to use d'Alembert inertial mechanics lead students to make frequent sign errors.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] A potential cause for these errors is the sign of the inertial forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Inertial forces can be used to describe an apparent force in a non-inertial reference frame that has an acceleration $\mathbf {a}$ with respect to an inertial reference frame.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] An extension of d'Alembert's principle can be used in thermodynamics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] Here $T=\partial V/\partial S$ is the temperature of the system, $\mathbf {F} _{i}$ are the external forces, $\mathbf {C} _{i}$ are the internal dissipative forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/d-alembert-s-principle] For $\delta S={\dot {S}}=0$ the classical d'Alembert principle and equations are recovered.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In the calculus of variations and classical mechanics, the **Euler–Lagrange equations** are a system of second-order ordinary differential equations whose solutions are stationary points of the given action functional.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The equations were discovered in the 1750s by Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler and Italian mathematician Joseph-Louis Lagrange.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Because a differentiable functional is stationary at its local extrema, the Euler–Lagrange equation is useful for solving optimization problems in which, given some functional, one seeks the function minimizing or maximizing it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] This is analogous to Fermat's theorem in calculus, stating that at any point where a differentiable function attains a local extremum its derivative is zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In Lagrangian mechanics, according to Hamilton's principle of stationary action, the evolution of a physical system is described by the solutions to the Euler equation for the action of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In this context Euler equations are usually called **Lagrange equations**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical mechanics, it is equivalent to Newton's laws of motion; indeed, the Euler–Lagrange equations will produce the same equations as Newton's Laws.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] This is particularly useful when analyzing systems whose force vectors are particularly complicated.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] It has the advantage that it takes the same form in any system of generalized coordinates, and it is better suited to generalizations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical field theory there is an analogous equation to calculate the dynamics of a field.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The Euler–Lagrange equation was developed in the 1750s by Euler and Lagrange in connection with their studies of the tautochrone problem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] This is the problem of determining a curve on which a weighted particle will fall to a fixed point in a fixed amount of time, independent of the starting point.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Lagrange solved this problem in 1755 and sent the solution to Euler.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Both further developed Lagrange's method and applied it to mechanics, which led to the formulation of Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Their correspondence ultimately led to the calculus of variations, a term coined by Euler himself in 1766.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Let $(X,L)$ be a real dynamical system with n degrees of freedom.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] (For those familiar with differential geometry, X is a smooth manifold, and $L\colon {\mathbb {R} }_{t}\times TX\to {\mathbb {R} },$ where $TX$ is the tangent bundle of X ).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] When we say stationary point, we mean a stationary point of S with respect to any small perturbation in ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] See proofs below for more rigorous detail.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The derivation of the one-dimensional Euler–Lagrange equation is one of the classic proofs in mathematics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] It relies on the fundamental lemma of calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] We assume that L is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] A weaker assumption can be used, but the proof becomes more difficult.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] If f extremizes the functional subject to the boundary conditions, then any slight perturbation of f that preserves the boundary values must either increase J (if f is a minimizer) or decrease J (if f is a maximizer).
