[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The third line follows from the fact that x does not depend on $\varepsilon$ , i.e. ${\frac {\mathrm {d} x}{\mathrm {d} \varepsilon }}=0$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] Given a functional $J=\int _{a}^{b}L(t,y(t),y'(t))\,\mathrm {d} t$ on $C^{1}([a,b])$ with the boundary conditions $y(a)=A$ and $y(b)=B$ , we proceed by approximating the extremal curve by a polygonal line with n segments and passing to the limit as the number of segments grows arbitrarily large.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The left hand side of the previous equation is the functional derivative $\delta J/\delta y$ of the functional J .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] A necessary condition for a differentiable functional to have an extremum on some function is that its functional derivative at that function vanishes, which is granted by the last equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] A standard example is finding the real-valued function *y*(*x*) on the interval [*a*, *b*], such that *y*(*a*) = *c* and *y*(*b*) = *d*, for which the path length along the curve traced by *y* is as short as possible.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] that is, the function must have a constant first derivative, and thus its graph is a straight line.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] In such cases, the coordinate *qk* is called a **cyclic coordinate**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] For example, if we use polar coordinates t, r, θ to describe the planar motion of a particle, and if *L* does not depend on θ, the conjugate momentum is the conserved angular momentum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] under fixed boundary conditions for the function itself as well as for the first $k-1$ derivatives (i.e. for all $f^{(i)},i\in \{0,...,k-1\}$ ).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/euler-lagrange-equation] The endpoint values of the highest derivative $f^{(k)}$ remain flexible.
