[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] In analytical mechanics, **generalized coordinates** are a set of parameters used to represent the configuration of a system in a configuration space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] These parameters must uniquely define the configuration of the system relative to a reference configuration.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The **generalized velocities** are the time derivatives of the generalized coordinates of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The adjective "generalized" distinguishes these parameters from the traditional use of the term "coordinate" to refer to Cartesian coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] An example of a generalized coordinate would be to describe the position of a pendulum using the angle of the pendulum relative to vertical, rather than by the x and y position of the pendulum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Although there may be many possible choices for generalized coordinates for a physical system, they are generally selected to simplify calculations, such as the solution of the equations of motion for the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] If the coordinates are independent of one another, the number of independent generalized coordinates is defined by the number of degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Generalized coordinates are paired with generalized momenta to provide canonical coordinates on phase space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] One generalized coordinate (one degree of freedom) on paths in 2D.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Only one generalized coordinate is needed to uniquely specify positions on the curve.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] is related to the other by the equations of the curves.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Multiple intersections of radius with path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Generalized coordinates are usually selected to provide the minimum number of independent coordinates that define the configuration of a system, which simplifies the formulation of Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] However, it can also occur that a useful set of generalized coordinates may be *dependent*, which means that they are related by one or more constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Two generalized coordinates, two degrees of freedom, on curved surfaces in 3D.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] are needed to specify the points on the curve, one possibility is shown for each case.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] are not necessary because any two determines the third according to the equations of the curves.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Any of the position vectors can be denoted **r***k* where *k* = 1, 2, …, *N* labels the particles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] which connects all the 3 spatial coordinates of that particle together, so they are not independent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The constraint may change with time, so time t will appear explicitly in the constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] At any instant of time, any one coordinate will be determined from the other coordinates, e.g. if xk and zk are given, then so is yk.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] One constraint equation counts as *one* constraint.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] If there are C constraints, each has an equation, so there will be C constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] There is not necessarily one constraint equation for each particle, and if there are no constraints on the system then there are no constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] So far, the configuration of the system is defined by 3*N* quantities, but C coordinates can be eliminated, one coordinate from each constraint equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The number of independent coordinates is *n* = 3*N* − *C*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] (In D dimensions, the original configuration would need ND coordinates, and the reduction by constraints means *n* = *ND* − *C*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] It is ideal to use the minimum number of coordinates needed to define the configuration of the entire system, while taking advantage of the constraints on the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] These quantities are known as **generalized coordinates** in this context, denoted *qj*(*t*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] which is a point in the *configuration space* of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] They are all independent of one other, and each is a function of time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Geometrically they can be lengths along straight lines, or arc lengths along curves, or angles; not necessarily Cartesian coordinates or other standard orthogonal coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] There is one for each degree of freedom, so the number of generalized coordinates equals the number of degrees of freedom, n.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] A degree of freedom corresponds to one quantity that changes the configuration of the system, for example the angle of a pendulum, or the arc length traversed by a bead along a wire.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] If it is possible to find from the constraints as many independent variables as there are degrees of freedom, these can be used as generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] and the generalized coordinates can be thought of as parameters associated with the constraint.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] (each dot over a quantity indicates one time derivative).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] and so generally depends on the generalized velocities and coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Since we are free to specify the initial values of the generalized coordinates and velocities separately, the generalized coordinates qj and velocities *dqj*/*dt* can be treated as *independent variables*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] A mechanical system can involve constraints on both the generalized coordinates and their derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Constraints of this type are known as non-holonomic.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] An example of such a constraint is a rolling wheel or knife-edge that constrains the direction of the velocity vector.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Non-holonomic constraints can also involve next-order derivatives such as generalized accelerations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The kinetic energy is a function only of the velocities **v***k*, not the coordinates **r***k* themselves.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] which illustrates the kinetic energy is in general a function of the generalized velocities, coordinates, and time if the constraints also vary with time, so *T* = *T*(**q**, *d***q**/*dt*, *t*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] In the case the constraints on the particles are time-independent, then all partial derivatives with respect to time are zero, and the kinetic energy is a homogeneous function of degree 2 in the generalized velocities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] and dividing by the square differential in time, *dt*2, to obtain the velocity squared of particle k.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Thus for time-independent constraints it is sufficient to know the line element to quickly obtain the kinetic energy of particles and hence the Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] It is instructive to see the various cases of polar coordinates in 2D and 3D, owing to their frequent appearance.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] This is a suitable choice of generalized coordinate for the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Only *one* coordinate is needed instead of two, because the position of the bead can be parameterized by one number, s, and the constraint equation connects the two coordinates x and y; either one is determined from the other.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The constraint force is the reaction force the wire exerts on the bead to keep it on the wire, and the non-constraint applied force is gravity acting on the bead.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Suppose the wire changes its shape with time, by flexing.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] which now both depend on time t due to the changing coordinates as the wire changes its shape.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Notice time appears implicitly via the coordinates *and* explicitly in the constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The relationship between the use of generalized coordinates and Cartesian coordinates to characterize the movement of a mechanical system can be illustrated by considering the constrained dynamics of a simple pendulum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] A simple pendulum consists of a mass M hanging from a pivot point so that it is constrained to move on a circle of radius L.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The position of the mass is defined by the coordinate vector **r** = (*x*, *y*) measured in the plane of the circle such that y is in the vertical direction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Now introduce the parameter θ, that defines the angular position of M from the vertical direction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The use of θ to define the configuration of this system avoids the constraint provided by the equation of the circle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] where g is the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Notice that the coefficient of δ*y* is the y-component of the applied force.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] This formulation yields one equation because there is a single parameter and no constraint equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] This shows that the parameter θ is a generalized coordinate that can be used in the same way as the Cartesian coordinates x and y to analyze the pendulum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The benefits of generalized coordinates become apparent with the analysis of a double pendulum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The formulation of Lagrange's equations for this system yields six equations in the four Cartesian coordinates *xi*, *yi* (*i* = 1, 2) and the two Lagrange multipliers *λi* (*i* = 1, 2) that arise from the two constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Now introduce the generalized coordinates *θi* (*i* = 1, 2) that define the angular position of each mass of the double pendulum from the vertical direction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The use of the generalized coordinates *θi* (*i* = 1, 2) provides an alternative to the Cartesian formulation of the dynamics of the double pendulum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] in which (*θ*, *φ*) are the spherical polar angles because the bob moves in the surface of a sphere.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The position **r** is measured along the suspension point to the bob, here treated as a point particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] A logical choice of generalized coordinates to describe the motion are the angles (*θ*, *φ*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] Only two coordinates are needed instead of three, because the position of the bob can be parameterized by two numbers, and the constraint equation connects the three coordinates (*x*, *y*, *z*) so any one of them is determined from the other two.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] The *principle of virtual work* states that if a system is in static equilibrium, the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for all virtual movements of the system from this state, that is, δ*W* = 0 for any variation δ**r**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] When formulated in terms of generalized coordinates, this is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *F**i* = 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] where δ**r***j* (*j* = 1, 2, …, *m*) denote the virtual displacements of each point in the body.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] are the generalized forces acting on the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/generalized-coordinates] where **v***j* is the velocity of the point of application of the force **F***j*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In physics, **Lagrangian mechanics** is an alternate formulation of classical mechanics founded on the d'Alembert principle of virtual work.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] It was introduced by the Italian-French mathematician and astronomer Joseph-Louis Lagrange in his presentation to the Turin Academy of Science in 1760 culminating in his 1788 grand opus, *Mécanique analytique*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Lagrange's approach greatly simplifies the analysis of many problems in mechanics, and it had crucial influence on other branches of physics, including relativity and quantum field theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Lagrangian mechanics describes a mechanical system as a pair (*M*, *L*) consisting of a configuration space *M* and a smooth function ${\textstyle L}$ within that space called a ***Lagrangian***.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For many systems, *L* = *T* − *V*, where *T* and *V* are the kinetic and potential energy of the system, respectively.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The stationary action principle requires that the action functional of the system derived from *L* must remain at a stationary point (specifically, a maximum, minimum, or saddle point) throughout the time evolution of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This constraint allows the calculation of the equations of motion of the system using Lagrange's equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Newton's laws and the concept of forces are the usual starting point for teaching about mechanical systems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This method works well for many problems, but for others the approach is nightmarishly complicated.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Lagrangian mechanics adopts energy rather than force as its basic ingredient, leading to more abstract equations capable of tackling more complex problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This summed quantity is minimized along the path that the particle actually takes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This choice eliminates the need for the constraint force to enter into the resultant generalized system of equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] There are fewer equations since one is not directly calculating the influence of the constraint on the particle at a given moment.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For a wide variety of physical systems, if the size and shape of a massive object are negligible, it is a useful simplification to treat it as a point particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In three-dimensional space, each position vector requires three coordinates to uniquely define the location of a point, so there are 3*N* coordinates to uniquely define the configuration of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] These are all specific points in space to locate the particles; a general point in space is written **r** = (*x*, *y*, *z*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The second law "net force equals mass times acceleration", $\sum \mathbf {F} =m{\frac {d^{2}\mathbf {r} }{dt^{2}}},$ applies to each particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For an *N*-particle system in 3 dimensions, there are 3*N* second-degree ordinary differential equations in the positions of the particles to solve for.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Instead of forces, Lagrangian mechanics uses the energies in the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The central quantity of Lagrangian mechanics is the **Lagrangian**, a function which summarizes the dynamics of the entire system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Overall, the Lagrangian has units of energy, but no single expression for all physical systems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Any function which generates the correct equations of motion, in agreement with physical laws, can be taken as a Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] It is nevertheless possible to construct general expressions for large classes of applications.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The *non-relativistic* Lagrangian for a system of particles in the absence of an electromagnetic field is given by $L=T-V,$ where $T={\frac {1}{2}}\sum _{k=1}^{N}m_{k}v_{k}^{2}$ is the total kinetic energy of the system, equaling the sum Σ of the kinetic energies of the N particles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Each particle labeled k has mass $m_{k},$ and *v**k*2 = **v***k* · **v***k* is the magnitude squared of its velocity, equivalent to the dot product of the velocity with itself.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Kinetic energy *T* is the energy of the system's motion and is a function only of the velocities **v***k*, not the positions **r***k*, nor time *t*, so *T* = *T*(**v**1, **v**2, ...).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] An equivalent but more mathematically formal definition of the Lagrangian is as follows.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The Lagrangian is a smooth function: $L:TQ\times \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ,$ where $TQ\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{6N}$ is the tangent bundle of the configuration space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] That is, each element in $TQ$ represents both the positions and the velocities of the particles, and can be written as a tuple $(q_{1},\ldots ,q_{N},{\dot {q}}_{1},\ldots {\dot {q}}_{N})$ with $q_{i}$ and ${\dot {q}}_{i}$ specifying a position and a velocity of the i'th particle respectively.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The time dependence $t\in \mathbb {R}$ allows for the Lagrangian to describe time-dependent forces or potentials.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] A trajectory of the system is a smooth function $q:[t_{0},t_{1}]\to Q,$ describing the evolution of the configuration over time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Its velocity is the time derivative ${\dot {q}}(t)\in T_{q(t)}Q$ of $q(t)$ , and the pair $(q(t),{\dot {q}}(t))\in TQ$ is thus an element of the bundle for any t .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The laws of motion in Lagrangian mechanics are derived from the postulate that among all trajectories between two given configurations, the actual one that will be taken by the system must be a critical point (often but not necessarily a local minimum) of the action functional.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This leads to the Euler–Lagrange equations (see also below).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The potential energy $V(q,t)$ depends only on the configuration (and possibly on time), and typically arises from conservative forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This formulation covers both conservative and time-dependent systems and forms the basis for generalizations to continuous systems (fields), constrained systems, and systems with curved configuration spaces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If *T* or *V* or both depend explicitly on time due to time-varying constraints or external influences, the Lagrangian *L*(**r**1, **r**2, ...
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If neither the potential nor the kinetic energy depend on time, then the Lagrangian *L*(**r**1, **r**2, ...
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In either case, the Lagrangian always has implicit time dependence through the generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Each overdot is a shorthand for a time derivative.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This procedure does increase the number of equations to solve compared to Newton's laws, from 3*N* to 3*N* + *C*, because there are 3*N* coupled second-order differential equations in the position coordinates and multipliers, plus *C* constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] However, when solved alongside the position coordinates of the particles, the multipliers can yield information about the constraint forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The coordinates do not need to be eliminated by solving the constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In each constraint equation, one coordinate is redundant because it is determined from the other coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The number of *independent* coordinates is therefore *n* = 3*N* − *C*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] We can transform each position vector to a common set of *n* generalized coordinates, conveniently written as an *n*-tuple **q** = (*q*1, *q*2, ...
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The vector **q** is a point in the configuration space of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] are mathematical results from the calculus of variations, which can also be used in mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Substituting in the Lagrangian *L*(**q**, d**q**/d*t*, *t*) gives the equations of motion of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The number of equations has decreased compared to Newtonian mechanics, from 3*N* to *n* = 3*N* − *C* coupled second-order differential equations in the generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] These equations do not include constraint forces at all, only non-constraint forces need to be accounted for.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Although the equations of motion include partial derivatives, the results of the partial derivatives are still ordinary differential equations in the position coordinates of the particles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The total time derivative denoted d/d*t* often involves implicit differentiation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Both equations are linear in the Lagrangian, but generally are nonlinear coupled equations in the coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] As already noted, this form of *L* is applicable to many important classes of system, but not everywhere.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For relativistic Lagrangian mechanics it must be replaced as a whole by a function consistent with special relativity (scalar under Lorentz transformations) or general relativity (4-scalar).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Where a magnetic field is present, the expression for the potential energy needs restating.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] And for dissipative forces (e.g., friction), another function must be introduced alongside Lagrangian often referred to as a "Rayleigh dissipation function" to account for the loss of energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] One or more of the particles may each be subject to one or more holonomic constraints; such a constraint is described by an equation of the form *f*(**r**, *t*) = 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If the number of constraints in the system is *C*, then each constraint has an equation *f*1(**r**, *t*) = 0, *f*2(**r**, *t*) = 0, ..., *fC*(**r**, *t*) = 0, each of which could apply to any of the particles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If particle *k* is subject to constraint *i*, then *fi*(**r***k*, *t*) = 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] At any instant of time, the coordinates of a constrained particle are linked together and not independent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The constraint equations determine the allowed paths the particles can move along, but not where they are or how fast they go at every instant of time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Nonholonomic constraints depend on the particle velocities, accelerations, or higher derivatives of position.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Lagrangian mechanics *can only be applied to systems whose constraints, if any, are all holonomic*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Three examples of nonholonomic constraints are: when the constraint equations are non-integrable, when the constraints have inequalities, or when the constraints involve complicated non-conservative forces like friction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Nonholonomic constraints require special treatment, and one may have to revert to Newtonian mechanics or use other methods.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For simplicity, Newton's laws can be illustrated for one particle without much loss of generality (for a system of *N* particles, all of these equations apply to each particle in the system).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The equation of motion for a particle of constant mass *m* is Newton's second law of 1687, in modern vector notation $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,$ where **a** is its acceleration and **F** the resultant force acting *on* it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Where the mass is varying, the equation needs to be generalised to take the time derivative of the momentum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In three spatial dimensions, this is a system of three coupled second-order ordinary differential equations to solve, since there are three components in this vector equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The solution is the position vector **r** of the particle at time *t*, subject to the initial conditions of **r** and **v** when *t* = 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Newton's laws are easy to use in Cartesian coordinates, but Cartesian coordinates are not always convenient, and for other coordinate systems the equations of motion can become complicated.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] All the indices *a*, *b*, *c*, each take the values 1, 2, 3.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Curvilinear coordinates are not the same as generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] It may seem like an overcomplication to cast Newton's law in this form, but there are advantages.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The acceleration components in terms of the Christoffel symbols can be avoided by evaluating derivatives of the kinetic energy instead.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If there is no resultant force acting on the particle, **F** = **0**, it does not accelerate, but moves with constant velocity in a straight line.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Mathematically, the solutions of the differential equation are *geodesics*, the curves of extremal length between two points in space (these may end up being minimal, that is the shortest paths, but not necessarily).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] In flat 3D real space the geodesics are simply straight lines.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] So for a free particle, Newton's second law coincides with the geodesic equation and states that free particles follow geodesics, the extremal trajectories it can move along.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If the particle is subject to forces **F** ≠ **0**, the particle accelerates due to forces acting on it and deviates away from the geodesics it would follow if free.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The constraint forces can be complicated, since they generally depend on time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Also, if there are constraints, the curvilinear coordinates are not independent but related by one or more constraint equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The constraint forces can either be eliminated from the equations of motion, so only the non-constraint forces remain, or included by including the constraint equations in the equations of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] A fundamental result in analytical mechanics is D'Alembert's principle, introduced in 1708 by Jacques Bernoulli to understand static equilibrium, and developed by D'Alembert in 1743 to solve dynamical problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The *virtual displacements*, $\delta \mathbf {r} _{k}$ , are by definition infinitesimal changes in the configuration of the system consistent with the constraint forces acting on the system *at an instant of time*, i.e. in such a way that the constraint forces maintain the constrained motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] They are not the same as the actual displacements in the system, which are caused by the resultant constraint and non-constraint forces acting on the particle to accelerate and move it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Virtual work is the work done along a virtual displacement for any force (constraint or non-constraint).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Thus D'Alembert's principle allows us to concentrate on only the applied non-constraint forces, and exclude the constraint forces in the equations of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The form shown is also independent of the choice of coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] However, it cannot be readily used to set up the equations of motion in an arbitrary coordinate system since the displacements $\delta \mathbf {r} _{k}$ might be connected by a constraint equation, which prevents us from setting the *N* individual summands to 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] We will therefore seek a system of mutually independent coordinates for which the total sum will be 0 if and only if the individual summands are 0.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Setting each of the summands to 0 will eventually give us our separated equations of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If there are constraints on particle *k*, then since the coordinates of the position **r***k* = (*x**k*, *y**k*, *z**k*) are linked together by a constraint equation, so are those of the virtual displacements *δ***r***k* = (*δx**k*, *δy**k*, *δz**k*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Since the generalized coordinates are independent, we can avoid the complications with the *δ***r***k* by converting to virtual displacements in the generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] There is no partial time derivative with respect to time multiplied by a time increment, since this is a virtual displacement, one along the constraints in an *instant* of time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This is half of the conversion to generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] It remains to convert the acceleration term into generalized coordinates, which is not immediately obvious.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] These equations are equivalent to Newton's laws *for the non-constraint forces*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The generalized forces in this equation are derived from the non-constraint forces only – the constraint forces have been excluded from D'Alembert's principle and do not need to be found.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The generalized forces may be non-conservative, provided they satisfy D'Alembert's principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] For a non-conservative force which depends on velocity, it *may* be possible to find a potential energy function *V* that depends on positions and velocities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] However, the Euler–Lagrange equations can only account for non-conservative forces *if* a potential can be found as shown.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] This may not always be possible for non-conservative forces, and Lagrange's equations do not involve any potential, only generalized forces; therefore they are more general than the Euler–Lagrange equations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The Euler–Lagrange equations also follow from the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Now, if the condition *δq**j*(*t*1) = *δq**j*(*t*2) = 0 holds for all *j*, the terms not integrated are zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] If in addition the entire time integral of *δL* is zero, then because the *δq**j* are independent, and the only way for a definite integral to be zero is if the integrand equals zero, each of the coefficients of *δq**j* must also be zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The time integral of the Lagrangian is another quantity called the action, defined as $S=\int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}L\,\mathrm {d} t,$ which is a *functional*; it takes in the Lagrangian function for all times between *t*1 and *t*2 and returns a scalar value.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Its dimensions are the same as [angular momentum], [energy]·[time], or [length]·[momentum].
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Instead of thinking about particles accelerating in response to applied forces, one might think of them picking out the path with a stationary action, with the end points of the path in configuration space held fixed at the initial and final times.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Hamilton's principle is one of several action principles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Newton himself was thinking along the lines of the variational calculus, but did not publish.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] These ideas in turn lead to the variational principles of mechanics, of Fermat, Maupertuis, Euler, Hamilton, and others.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Hamilton's principle can be applied to nonholonomic constraints if the constraint equations can be put into a certain form, a linear combination of first order differentials in the coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The resulting constraint equation can be rearranged into first order differential equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Hamilton's principle is still valid even if the coordinates *L* is expressed in are not independent, here **r***k*, but the constraints are still assumed to be holonomic.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] What cannot be done is to simply equate the coefficients of *δ***r***k* to zero because the *δ***r***k* are not independent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] Instead, the method of Lagrange multipliers can be used to include the constraints.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The Lagrange multipliers are arbitrary functions of time *t*, but not functions of the coordinates **r***k*, so the multipliers are on equal footing with the position coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p01] The introduced multipliers can be found so that the coefficients of *δ***r***k* are zero, even though the **r***k* are not independent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian of a given system is not unique.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] A Lagrangian *L* can be multiplied by a nonzero constant *a* and shifted by an arbitrary constant *b*, and the new Lagrangian *L*′ = *aL* + *b* will describe the same motion as *L*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The two derived relations can be employed in the proof.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] An important property of the Lagrangian is that conserved quantities can easily be read off from it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This is a special case of Noether's theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Such coordinates are called "cyclic" or "ignorable".
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] For example, a system may have a Lagrangian $L(r,\theta ,{\dot {s}},{\dot {z}},{\dot {r}},{\dot {\theta }},{\dot {\phi }},t),$ where *r* and *z* are lengths along straight lines, *s* is an arc length along some curve, and *θ* and *φ* are angles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Notice *z*, *s*, and *φ* are all absent in the Lagrangian even though their velocities are not.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] However complicated the motion of the system is, all the coordinates and velocities will vary in such a way that these momenta are conserved.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] At every time instant *t*, the energy is invariant under configuration space coordinate changes **q** → **Q**, i.e.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] (using natural coordinates) $E(\mathbf {q} ,{\dot {\mathbf {q} }},t)=E(\mathbf {Q} ,{\dot {\mathbf {Q} }},t).$ Besides this result, the proof below shows that, under such change of coordinates, the derivatives $\partial L/\partial {\dot {q}}_{i}$ change as coefficients of a linear form.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In Lagrangian mechanics, the system is closed if and only if its Lagrangian L does not explicitly depend on time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The energy conservation law states that the energy E of a closed system is an integral of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] (In other words, **q** satisfies the Euler–Lagrange equations).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Under all these circumstances, the constant $E=T+V$ is the total energy of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The kinetic and potential energies still change as the system evolves, but the motion of the system will be such that their sum, the total energy, is constant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This is a valuable simplification, since the energy *E* is a constant of integration that counts as an arbitrary constant for the problem, and it may be possible to integrate the velocities from this energy relation to solve for the coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Since the lengths and times have been scaled, the trajectories of the particles in the system follow geometrically similar paths differing in size.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If they do interact this is not possible.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This may be physically motivated by taking the non-interacting Lagrangians to be kinetic energies only, while the interaction Lagrangian is the system's total potential energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Also, in the limiting case of negligible interaction, *L**AB* tends to zero reducing to the non-interacting case above.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The extension to more than two non-interacting subsystems is straightforward – the overall Lagrangian is the sum of the separate Lagrangians for each subsystem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If there are interactions, then interaction Lagrangians may be added.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If the matrix W is non-singular, the above equations can be solved to represent ${\ddot {q}}$ as a function of $({\dot {q}},q,t)$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If the matrix is non-invertible, it would not be possible to represent all ${\ddot {q}}$ 's as a function of $({\dot {q}},q,t)$ but also, the Hamiltonian equations of motions will not take the standard form.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The following examples apply Lagrange's equations of the second kind to mechanical problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If there are more particles, in accordance with the above results, the total kinetic energy is a sum over all the particle kinetic energies, and the potential is a function of all the coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Collecting the equations in vector form we find $m{\ddot {\mathbf {r} }}=-{\boldsymbol {\nabla }}V$ which is Newton's second law of motion for a particle subject to a conservative force.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian in two-dimensional polar coordinates is recovered by fixing *θ* to the constant value *π*/2.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Consider a pendulum of mass *m* and length *ℓ*, which is attached to a support with mass *M*, which can move along a line in the x -direction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Let x be the coordinate along the line of the support, and let us denote the position of the pendulum by the angle $\theta$ from the vertical.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The generalized coordinates can be taken to be x and $\theta$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Since *x* is absent from the Lagrangian, it is a cyclic coordinate.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] These equations may look quite complicated, but finding them with Newton's laws would have required carefully identifying all forces, which would have been much more laborious and prone to errors.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Furthermore, it is trivial to obtain the results numerically, given suitable starting conditions and a chosen time step, by stepping through the results iteratively.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Two bodies of masses *m*1 and *m*2 with position vectors **r**1 and **r**2 are in orbit about each other due to an attractive central potential *V*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] We may write down the Lagrangian in terms of the position coordinates as they are, but it is an established procedure to convert the two-body problem into a one-body problem as follows.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian splits into a *center-of-mass* term *L*cm and a *relative motion* term *L*rel.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Euler–Lagrange equation for **R** is simply $M{\ddot {\mathbf {R} }}=0,$ which states the center of mass moves in a straight line at constant velocity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The radial coordinate *r* and angular velocity d*θ*/d*t* can vary with time, but only in such a way that *ℓ* is constant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This equation is identical to the radial equation obtained using Newton's laws in a *co-rotating* reference frame, that is, a frame rotating with the reduced mass so it appears stationary.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Of course, if one remains entirely within the one-dimensional formulation, *ℓ* enters only as some imposed parameter of the external outward force, and its interpretation as angular momentum depends upon the more general two-dimensional problem from which the one-dimensional problem originated.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If one arrives at this equation using Newtonian mechanics in a co-rotating frame, the interpretation is evident as the centrifugal force in that frame due to the rotation of the frame itself.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If one arrives at this equation directly by using the generalized coordinates (*r*, *θ*) and simply following the Lagrangian formulation without thinking about frames at all, the interpretation is that the centrifugal force is an outgrowth of *using polar coordinates*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] "Since such quantities are not true physical forces, they are often called *inertia forces*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This viewpoint, that fictitious forces originate in the choice of coordinates, often is expressed by users of the Lagrangian method.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This view arises naturally in the Lagrangian approach, because the frame of reference is (possibly unconsciously) selected by the choice of coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] For example, see for a comparison of Lagrangians in an inertial and in a noninertial frame of reference.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] See also the discussion of "total" and "updated" Lagrangian formulations in.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Unfortunately, this usage of "inertial force" conflicts with the Newtonian idea of an inertial force.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In the Newtonian view, an inertial force originates in the acceleration of the frame of observation (the fact that it is not an inertial frame of reference), not in the choice of coordinate system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] To keep matters clear, it is safest to refer to the Lagrangian inertial forces as *generalized* inertial forces, to distinguish them from the Newtonian vector inertial forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] That is, one should avoid following Hildebrand when he says (p.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] 155) "we deal *always* with *generalized* forces, velocities accelerations, and momenta.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] It is known that the Lagrangian of a system is not unique.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Within the Lagrangian formalism the Newtonian fictitious forces can be identified by the existence of alternative Lagrangians in which the fictitious forces disappear, sometimes found by exploiting the symmetry of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Dissipation (i.e. non-conservative systems) can also be treated with an effective Lagrangian formulated by a certain doubling of the degrees of freedom.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In a more general formulation, the forces could be both conservative and viscous.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] A test particle is a particle whose mass and charge are assumed to be so small that its effect on external system is insignificant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] It is often a hypothetical simplified point particle with no properties other than mass and charge.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Real particles like electrons and up quarks are more complex and have additional terms in their Lagrangians.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Not only can the fields form non conservative potentials, these potentials can also be velocity dependent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian for a charged particle with electrical charge *q*, interacting with an electromagnetic field, is the prototypical example of a velocity-dependent potential.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian of a massive charged test particle in an electromagnetic field $L={\tfrac {1}{2}}m{\dot {\mathbf {r} }}^{2}+q\,{\dot {\mathbf {r} }}\cdot \mathbf {A} -q\phi ,$ is called minimal coupling.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This is a good example of when the common rule of thumb that the Lagrangian is the kinetic energy minus the potential energy is incorrect.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This relation is also used in the minimal coupling prescription in quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] From this expression, we can see that the canonical momentum **p** is not gauge invariant, and therefore not a measurable physical quantity; However, if **r** is cyclic (i.e.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Lagrangian is independent of position **r**), which happens if the *ϕ* and **A** fields are uniform, then this canonical momentum **p** given here is the conserved momentum, while the measurable physical kinetic momentum *m***v** is not.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The ideas in Lagrangian mechanics have numerous applications in other areas of physics, and can adopt generalized results from the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] A closely related formulation of classical mechanics is Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Hamiltonian is defined by $H=\sum _{i=1}^{n}{\dot {q}}_{i}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{i}}}-L$ and can be obtained by performing a Legendre transformation on the Lagrangian, which introduces new variables canonically conjugate to the original variables.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] For example, given a set of generalized coordinates, the variables canonically conjugate are the generalized momenta.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This doubles the number of variables, but makes differential equations first order.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Hamiltonian is a particularly ubiquitous quantity in quantum mechanics (see Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Routhian mechanics is a hybrid formulation of Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, which is not often used in practice but an efficient formulation for cyclic coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Euler–Lagrange equations can also be formulated in terms of the generalized momenta rather than generalized coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Performing a Legendre transformation on the generalized coordinate Lagrangian *L*(**q**, d**q**/d*t*, *t*) obtains the generalized momenta Lagrangian *L*′(**p**, d**p**/d*t*, *t*) in terms of the original Lagrangian, as well the EL equations in terms of the generalized momenta.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Both Lagrangians contain the same information, and either can be used to solve for the motion of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In practice generalized coordinates are more convenient to use and interpret than generalized momenta.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] There is no mathematical reason to restrict the derivatives of generalized coordinates to first order only.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] It is possible to derive modified EL equations for a Lagrangian containing higher order derivatives, see Euler–Lagrange equation for details.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Lagrangian mechanics can be applied to geometrical optics, by applying variational principles to rays of light in a medium, and solving the EL equations gives the equations of the paths the light rays follow.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Lagrangian mechanics can be formulated in special relativity and general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Some features of Lagrangian mechanics are retained in the relativistic theories but difficulties quickly appear in other respects.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In particular, the EL equations take the same form, and the connection between cyclic coordinates and conserved momenta still applies, however the Lagrangian must be modified and is not simply the kinetic minus the potential energy of a particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Also, it is not straightforward to handle multiparticle systems in a manifestly covariant way, it may be possible if a particular frame of reference is singled out.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In quantum mechanics, action and quantum-mechanical phase are related via the Planck constant, and the principle of stationary action can be understood in terms of constructive interference of wave functions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In 1948, Feynman discovered the path integral formulation extending the principle of least action to quantum mechanics for electrons and photons.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In this formulation, particles travel every possible path between the initial and final states; the probability of a specific final state is obtained by summing over all possible trajectories leading to it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In the classical regime, the path integral formulation cleanly reproduces Hamilton's principle, and Fermat's principle in optics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In Lagrangian mechanics, the generalized coordinates form a discrete set of variables that define the configuration of a system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] In classical field theory, the physical system is not a set of discrete particles, but rather a continuous field *ϕ*(**r**, *t*) defined over a region of 3D space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Associated with the field is a Lagrangian density ${\mathcal {L}}(\phi ,\nabla \phi ,{\dot {\phi }},\mathbf {r} ,t)$ defined in terms of the field and its space and time derivatives at a location **r** and time *t*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] Analogous to the particle case, for non-relativistic applications the Lagrangian density is also the kinetic energy density of the field, minus its potential energy density (this is not true in general, and the Lagrangian density has to be "reverse engineered").
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian is then the volume integral of the Lagrangian density over 3D space $L(t)=\int {\mathcal {L}}\,\mathrm {d} ^{3}\mathbf {r}$ where d3**r** is a 3D differential volume element.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The Lagrangian is a function of time since the Lagrangian density has implicit space dependence via the fields, and may have explicit spatial dependence, but these are removed in the integral, leaving only time in as the variable for the Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] The action principle, and the Lagrangian formalism, are tied closely to Noether's theorem, which connects physical conserved quantities to continuous symmetries of a physical system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] If the Lagrangian is invariant under a symmetry, then the resulting equations of motion are also invariant under that symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/lagrangian-mechanics-p02] This characteristic is very helpful in showing that theories are consistent with either special relativity or general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Noether's theorem is used in theoretical physics and the calculus of variations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] It reveals the fundamental relation between the symmetries of a physical system and the conservation laws.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] It also made modern theoretical physicists much more focused on symmetries of physical systems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] A generalization of the formulations on constants of motion in Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics (developed in 1788 and 1833, respectively), it does not apply to systems that cannot be modeled with a Lagrangian alone (e.g., systems with a Rayleigh dissipation function).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In particular, dissipative systems with continuous symmetries need not have a corresponding conservation law.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The physical system itself need not be symmetric; a jagged asteroid tumbling in space conserves angular momentum despite its asymmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] It is the laws of its motion that are symmetric.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Noether's theorem is important, both because of the insight it gives into conservation laws, and also as a practical calculational tool.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] It allows investigators to determine the conserved quantities (invariants) from the observed symmetries of a physical system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Conversely, it allows researchers to consider whole classes of hypothetical Lagrangians with given invariants, to describe a physical system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] As an illustration, suppose that a physical theory is proposed which conserves a quantity *X*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] A researcher can calculate the types of Lagrangians that conserve *X* through a continuous symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Due to Noether's theorem, the properties of these Lagrangians provide further criteria to understand the implications and judge the fitness of the new theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] There are numerous versions of Noether's theorem, with varying degrees of generality.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] There are natural quantum counterparts of this theorem, expressed in the Ward–Takahashi identities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Generalizations of Noether's theorem to superspaces also exist.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The word "symmetry" in the above statement refers more precisely to the covariance of the form that a physical law takes with respect to a one-dimensional Lie group of transformations satisfying certain technical criteria.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation law of a physical quantity is usually expressed as a continuity equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The formal proof of the theorem utilizes the condition of invariance to derive an expression for a current associated with a conserved physical quantity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In modern terminology, the conserved quantity is called the *Noether charge*, while the flow carrying that charge is called the *Noether current*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The Noether current is defined up to a solenoidal (divergenceless) vector field.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The main idea behind Noether's theorem is most easily illustrated by a system with one coordinate q and a continuous symmetry $\varphi :q\mapsto q+\delta q$ (gray arrows on the diagram).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Consider any trajectory $q(t)$ (bold on the diagram) that satisfies the system's laws of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] That is, the action S governing this system is stationary on this trajectory, i.e. does not change under any local variation of the trajectory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In particular it would not change under a variation that applies the symmetry flow $\varphi$ on a time segment [*t*0, *t*1] and is motionless outside that segment.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] To keep the trajectory continuous, we use "buffering" periods of small time $\tau$ to transition between the segments gradually.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The total change in the action S now comprises changes brought by every interval in play.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Parts where variation itself vanishes, i.e. outside $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ , bring no $\Delta S$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The middle part does not change the action either, because its transformation $\varphi$ is a symmetry and thus preserves the Lagrangian L and the action ${\textstyle S=\int L}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The only remaining parts are the "buffering" pieces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] So the regions contribute mostly through their "slanting" ${\dot {q}}\rightarrow {\dot {q}}\pm \delta q/\tau$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] These last terms, evaluated around the endpoints $t_{0}$ and $t_{1}$ , should cancel each other in order to make the total change in the action $\Delta S$ be zero, as would be expected if the trajectory is a solution.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] That is $\left({\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}}}\varphi \right)(t_{0})=\left({\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}}}\varphi \right)(t_{1}),$ meaning the quantity $\left(\partial L/\partial {\dot {q}}\right)\varphi$ is conserved, which is the conclusion of Noether's theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For instance if pure translations of q by a constant are the symmetry, then the conserved quantity becomes just $\left(\partial L/\partial {\dot {q}}\right)=p$ , the canonical momentum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] A conservation law states that some quantity *X* in the mathematical description of a system's evolution remains constant throughout its motion – it is an invariant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Such quantities are said to be conserved; they are often called constants of motion (although motion *per se* need not be involved, just evolution in time).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, if the energy of a system is conserved, its energy is invariant at all times, which imposes a constraint on the system's motion and may help in solving for it.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Aside from insights that such constants of motion give into the nature of a system, they are a useful calculational tool; for example, an approximate solution can be corrected by finding the nearest state that satisfies the suitable conservation laws.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The earliest constants of motion discovered were momentum and kinetic energy, which were proposed in the 17th century by René Descartes and Gottfried Leibniz on the basis of collision experiments, and refined by subsequent researchers.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Isaac Newton was the first to enunciate the conservation of momentum in its modern form, and showed that it was a consequence of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The local conservation of non-gravitational linear momentum and energy in a free-falling reference frame is expressed by the vanishing of the covariant divergence of the stress–energy tensor.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Another important conserved quantity, discovered in studies of the celestial mechanics of astronomical bodies, is the Laplace–Runge–Lenz vector.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, physicists developed more systematic methods for discovering invariants.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] A major advance came in 1788 with the development of Lagrangian mechanics, which is related to the principle of least action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In this approach, the state of the system can be described by any type of generalized coordinates **q**; the laws of motion need not be expressed in a Cartesian coordinate system, as was customary in Newtonian mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Hamilton's principle states that the physical path **q**(*t*)—the one actually taken by the system—is a path for which infinitesimal variations in that path cause no change in *I*, at least up to first order.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] is conserved throughout the motion (on the physical path).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Thus, the absence of the **ignorable** coordinate *qk* from the Lagrangian implies that the Lagrangian is unaffected by changes or transformations of *qk*; the Lagrangian is invariant, and is said to exhibit a symmetry under such transformations.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] This is the seed idea generalized in Noether's theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Several alternative methods for finding conserved quantities were developed in the 19th century, especially by William Rowan Hamilton.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, he developed a theory of canonical transformations which allowed changing coordinates so that some coordinates disappeared from the Lagrangian, as above, resulting in conserved canonical momenta.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Another approach, and perhaps the most efficient for finding conserved quantities, is the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Emmy Noether's work on the invariance theorem began in 1915 when she was helping Felix Klein and David Hilbert with their work related to Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity By March 1918 she had most of the key ideas for the paper which would be published later in the year.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The essence of Noether's theorem is generalizing the notion of ignorable coordinates.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] One can assume that the Lagrangian *L* defined above is invariant under small perturbations (warpings) of the time variable *t* and the generalized coordinates **q**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] where the perturbations *δt* and *δ***q** are both small, but variable.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For generality, assume there are (say) *N* such symmetry transformations of the action, i.e. transformations leaving the action unchanged; labelled by an index *r* = 1, 2, 3, ..., *N*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For translations, **Q***r* is a constant with units of length; for rotations, it is an expression linear in the components of **q**, and the parameters make up an angle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For illustration, consider a Lagrangian that does not depend on time, i.e., that is invariant (symmetric) under changes *t* → *t* + δ*t*, without any change in the coordinates **q**.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Consider a Lagrangian which does not depend on an ("ignorable", as above) coordinate *q**k*; so it is invariant (symmetric) under changes *q**k* → *q**k* + *δq**k*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In special and general relativity, these two conservation laws can be expressed either *globally* (as it is done above), or *locally* as a continuity equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The global versions can be united into a single global conservation law: the conservation of the energy-momentum 4-vector.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The local versions of energy and momentum conservation (at any point in space-time) can also be united, into the conservation of a quantity defined *locally* at the space-time point: the stress–energy tensor(this will be derived in the next section).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation of the angular momentum **L** = **r** × **p** is analogous to its linear momentum counterpart.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] It is assumed that the symmetry of the Lagrangian is rotational, i.e., that the Lagrangian does not depend on the absolute orientation of the physical system in space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Since time is not being transformed, *T* = 0, and *N* = 1.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In other words, the component of the angular momentum **L** along the **n** axis is conserved.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] And if **n** is arbitrary, i.e., if the system is insensitive to any rotation, then every component of **L** is conserved; in short, angular momentum is conserved.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Although useful in its own right, the version of Noether's theorem given above is a special case of the general version derived in 1915.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] To give the flavor of the general theorem, a version of Noether's theorem for continuous fields in four-dimensional space–time is now given.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Since field theory problems are more common in modern physics than mechanics problems, this field theory version is the most commonly used version of Noether's theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] Let there be a set of differentiable fields $\varphi$ defined over all space and time; for example, the temperature $T(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ would be representative of such a field, being a number defined at every place and time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] (the theorem can be further generalized to the case where the Lagrangian depends on up to the *n*th derivative, and can also be formulated using jet bundles).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] where $\Psi$ is in general a function that may depend on both $x^{\mu }$ and $\varphi$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The condition for $\Psi$ to generate a physical symmetry is that the action ${\mathcal {S}}$ is left invariant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] since the integral of a divergence becomes a boundary term according to the divergence theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] (where the dot product is understood to contract the *field* indices, not the $\nu$ index or r index).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] which expresses the idea that the amount of a conserved quantity within a sphere cannot change unless some of it flows out of the sphere.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, electric charge is conserved; the amount of charge within a sphere cannot change unless charge enters or leaves the sphere.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] For illustration, consider a physical system of fields that behaves the same under translations in time and space, as considered above; in other words, $L\left({\boldsymbol {\varphi }},\partial _{\mu }{\boldsymbol {\varphi }},x^{\mu }\right)$ is constant in its third argument.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In that case, *N* = 4, one for each dimension of space and time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] and thus Noether's theorem corresponds to the conservation law for the stress–energy tensor *T**μ**ν*, where we have used $\mu$ in place of r .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] (we relabelled $\mu$ as $\sigma$ at an intermediate step to avoid conflict).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation of electric charge, by contrast, can be derived by considering *Ψ* linear in the fields *φ* rather than in the derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In quantum mechanics, the probability amplitude *ψ*(**x**) of finding a particle at a point **x** is a complex field *φ*, because it ascribes a complex number to every point in space and time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] The probability amplitude itself is physically unmeasurable; only the probability *p* = |*ψ*|2 can be inferred from a set of measurements.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] In the limit when the phase *θ* becomes infinitesimally small, *δθ*, it may be taken as the parameter *ε*, while the *Ψ* are equal to *iψ* and −*iψ**, respectively.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] which, when multiplied by the charge on that species of particle, equals the electric current density due to that type of particle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p01] This "gauge invariance" was first noted by Hermann Weyl, and is one of the prototype gauge symmetries of physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Consider the simplest case, a system with one independent variable, time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] is invariant under brief infinitesimal variations in the dependent variables.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] And suppose that the integral is invariant under a continuous symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] where *ε* is a real variable indicating the amount of flow, and *T* is a real constant (which could be zero) indicating how much the flow shifts time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] which may be regarded as a function of *ε*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] is a constant of the motion, i.e., it is a conserved quantity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] To avoid excessive complication of the formulas, this derivation assumed that the flow does not change as time passes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The same result can be obtained in the more general case.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\textstyle {\cal {P}}}$ is a closed path in ${\textstyle {\cal {D}}}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Here, the *function* ${\textstyle S(\mathbf {q} ,t)}$ is the action *function* that is computed by the integration of the Lagrangian over optimal trajectories or equivalently obtained through the Hamilton-Jacobi equation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] As ${\textstyle \partial S/\partial \mathbf {q} =\mathbf {p} }$ (where ${\textstyle \mathbf {p} }$ is the momentum) and ${\textstyle \partial S/\partial t=-H}$ (where ${\textstyle H}$ is the Hamiltonian), the differential of this function is given by ${\textstyle dS=\mathbf {p} d\mathbf {q} -Hdt}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Using the geometrical approach, the conserved quantity for a symmetry in Noether's sense can be derived.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The closed path ${\textstyle {\cal {P}}}$ of integration is chosen as ${\textstyle ABB'A'}$ , where the branches ${\textstyle AB}$ and ${\textstyle A'B'}$ are given ${\textstyle {\cal {C}}}$ and ${\textstyle {\cal {C}}'}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Therefore, to the first order in ${\textstyle \epsilon }$ , the quantity $I=\mathbf {p} \phi _{\mathbf {q} }-H\phi _{t}$ is conserved along the trajectory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem may also be derived for tensor fields $\varphi ^{A}$ where the index *A* ranges over the various components of the various tensor fields.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] These field quantities are functions defined over a four-dimensional space whose points are labeled by coordinates *x*μ where the index *μ* ranges over time (*μ* = 0) and three spatial dimensions (*μ* = 1, 2, 3).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] These four coordinates are the independent variables; and the values of the fields at each event are the dependent variables.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] By this definition, the field variations $\delta \varphi ^{A}$ result from two factors: intrinsic changes in the field themselves and changes in coordinates, since the transformed field *α**A* depends on the transformed coordinates ξμ.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] If the coordinates are changed, the boundary of the region of space–time over which the Lagrangian is being integrated also changes; the original boundary and its transformed version are denoted as Ω and Ω', respectively.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem begins with the assumption that a specific transformation of the coordinates and field variables does not change the action, which is defined as the integral of the Lagrangian density over the given region of spacetime.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] where the comma subscript indicates a partial derivative with respect to the coordinate(s) that follows the comma, e.g.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\mathcal {L}}_{X}\varphi ^{A}$ is the Lie derivative of $\varphi ^{A}$ in the *X**μ* direction.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we have an *n*-dimensional oriented Riemannian or more generally Lorentzian manifold, *M* and a target manifold *T*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be the configuration space of smooth functions from *M* to *T*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] To get to the usual version of Noether's theorem, we need additional restrictions on the action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] called the Lagrangian density, depending on $\varphi$ , its derivative and the position.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we are given boundary conditions, i.e., a specification of the value of $\varphi$ at the boundary if *M* is compact, or some limit on $\varphi$ as *x* approaches ∞.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] and that $\varphi$ satisfies the given boundary conditions, is the subspace of on shell solutions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] If this holds on shell and off shell, we say *Q* generates an off-shell symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] If this only holds on shell, we say *Q* generates an on-shell symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] If the symmetry generated by *Q* integrates to a continuous symmetry, we say that *Q* is the generator of a one parameter symmetry Lie group.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] which is called the **Noether current** associated with the symmetry.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The continuity equation tells us that if we integrate this current over a space-like slice, we get a conserved quantity called the Noether charge (provided, of course, if *M* is noncompact, the currents fall off sufficiently fast at infinity).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem is an on shell theorem: it relies on the use of the equations of motion—the classical path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] It reflects the relation between the boundary conditions and the variational principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The quantum analogs of Noether's theorem involving expectation values (e.g., ${\textstyle \left\langle \int \partial \cdot {\textbf {J}}~d^{4}x\right\rangle =0}$ ) probing off shell quantities as well are the Ward–Takahashi identities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we have two symmetry derivations *Q*1 and *Q*2.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Then, [*Q*1, *Q*2] is also a symmetry derivation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] This shows we can extend Noether's theorem to larger Lie algebras in a natural way.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] This applies to *any* local symmetry derivation *Q* satisfying *QS* ≈ 0, and also to more general local functional differentiable actions, including ones where the Lagrangian depends on higher derivatives of the fields.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Let *ε* be any arbitrary smooth function of the spacetime (or time) manifold such that the closure of its support is disjoint from the boundary.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] This is the generalization of Noether's theorem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] To see how the generalization is related to the version given above, assume that the action is the spacetime integral of a Lagrangian that only depends on $\varphi$ and its first derivatives.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Looking at the specific case of a Newtonian particle of mass *m*, coordinate *x*, moving under the influence of a potential *V*, coordinatized by time *t*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The first term in the brackets is the kinetic energy of the particle, while the second is its potential energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Consider the generator of time translations $Q={\frac {d}{dt}}$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The right hand side is the energy, and Noether's theorem states that $dj/dt=0$ (i.e. the principle of conservation of energy is a consequence of invariance under time translations).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] for N Newtonian particles where the potential only depends pairwise upon the relative displacement.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] For ${\vec {Q}}$ , consider the generator of Galilean transformations (i.e. a change in the frame of reference).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\vec {P}}$ is the total momentum, *M* is the total mass and ${\vec {x}}_{CM}$ is the center of mass.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Both examples 1 and 2 are over a 1-dimensional manifold (time).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] An example involving spacetime is a conformal transformation of a massless real scalar field with a quartic potential in (3 + 1)-Minkowski spacetime.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] For *Q*, consider the generator of a spacetime rescaling.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The second term on the right hand side is due to the "conformal weight" of $\varphi$ .
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem states that $\partial _{\mu }j^{\mu }=0$ (as one may explicitly check by substituting the Euler–Lagrange equations into the left hand side).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] If one tries to find the Ward–Takahashi analog of this equation, one runs into a problem because of anomalies.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] Application of Noether's theorem allows physicists to gain insights into any general theory in physics, by just analyzing the various transformations that would make the form of the laws involved invariant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/noether-s-theorem-p02] The Noether charge is also used in calculating the entropy of stationary black holes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Several distinct action principles differ in the constraints on their initial and final conditions.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The names of action principles have evolved over time and differ in details of the endpoints of the paths and the nature of the variation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Quantum action principles generalize and justify the older classical principles by showing they are a direct result of quantum interference patterns.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are the basis for Feynman's version of quantum mechanics, general relativity and quantum field theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action principles have applications as broad as physics, including many problems in classical mechanics but especially in modern problems of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] These applications increased and expanded over two centuries as the power of the method and its further mathematical development rose.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] This article introduces the action principle concepts and summarizes other articles with more details on concepts and specific principles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are "integral" approaches rather than the "differential" approach of Newtonian mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The core ideas are based on energy, paths, an energy function called the Lagrangian along paths, and selection of a path according to the "action", a continuous sum or integral of the Lagrangian along the path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Introductory study of mechanics, the science of interacting objects, typically begins with Newton's laws based on the concept of force, defined by the acceleration it causes when applied to mass: *F* = *ma*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] This approach to mechanics focuses on a single point in space and time, attempting to answer the question: "What happens next?".
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Mechanics based on action principles begin with the concept of action, an energy tradeoff between kinetic energy and potential energy, defined by the physics of the problem.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] These approaches answer questions relating starting and ending points: Which trajectory will place a basketball in the hoop?
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] If we launch a rocket to the Moon today, how can it land there in 5 days?
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The Newtonian and action-principle forms are equivalent, and either one can solve the same problems, but selecting the appropriate form will make solutions much easier.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The energy function in the action principles is not the total energy (conserved in an isolated system), but the Lagrangian, the difference between kinetic and potential energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The kinetic energy combines the energy of motion for all the objects in the system; the potential energy depends upon the instantaneous position of the objects and drives the motion of the objects.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The motion of the objects places them in new positions with new potential energy values, giving a new value for the Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Using energy rather than force gives immediate advantages as a basis for mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Force mechanics involves three-dimensional vector calculus, with three space and three momentum coordinates for each object in the scenario; energy is a scalar magnitude combining information from all objects, giving an immediate simplification in many cases.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The components of force vary with coordinate systems; the energy value is the same in all coordinate systems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Force requires an inertial frame of reference; once velocities approach the speed of light, special relativity profoundly affects mechanics based on forces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In action principles, relativity merely requires a different Lagrangian: the principle itself is independent of coordinate systems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The explanatory diagrams in force-based mechanics usually focus on a single point, like the center of momentum, and show vectors of forces and velocities.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The explanatory diagrams of action-based mechanics have two points with actual and possible paths connecting them.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] These diagrammatic conventions reiterate the different strong points of each method.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Depending on the action principle, the two points connected by paths in a diagram may represent two particle positions at different times, or the two points may represent values in a configuration space or in a phase space.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The mathematical technology and terminology of action principles can be learned by thinking in terms of physical space, then applied in the more powerful and general abstract spaces.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles assign a number—the action—to each possible path between two points.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] where the form of the kinetic energy (KE) and potential energy (PE) expressions depend upon the physics problem, and their value at each point on the path depends upon relative coordinates corresponding to that point.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The energy function is called a Lagrangian; in simple problems it is the kinetic energy minus the potential energy of the system.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In classical mechanics, a system moving between two points takes one particular path; other similar paths are not taken.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Each conceivable path corresponds to a value of the action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] An action principle predicts or explains that the particular path taken has a stationary value for the system's action: similar paths near the one taken have very similar action value.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] This variation in the action value is key to the action principles.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In quantum mechanics, every possible path contributes an amplitude to the system's behavior, with the phase of each amplitude determined by the action for that path (phase = ⁠action/ħ⁠).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] When the scale of the problem is much larger than the Planck constant ħ (the classical limit), only the stationary action path survives the interference.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] meaning that at the stationary point, the variation of the action S with some fixed constraints C is zero.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For action principles, the stationary point may be a minimum or a saddle point, but not a maximum.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Elliptical planetary orbits provide a simple example of two paths with equal action – one in each direction around the orbit; neither can be the minimum or "least action".
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The path variation implied by δ is not the same as a differential like dt.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action integral depends on the coordinates of the objects, and these coordinates depend upon the path taken.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Thus the action integral is a functional, a function of a function.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] An important result from geometry known as Noether's theorem states that any conserved quantities in a Lagrangian imply a continuous symmetry and conversely.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For examples, a Lagrangian independent of time corresponds to a system with conserved energy; spatial translation independence implies momentum conservation; angular rotation invariance implies angular momentum conservation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] These examples are global symmetries, where the independence is itself independent of space or time; more general *local* symmetries having a functional dependence on space or time lead to gauge theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The observed conservation of isospin was used by Yang Chen-Ning and Robert Mills in 1953 to construct a gauge theory for mesons, leading some decades later to modern particle physics theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles apply to a wide variety of physical problems, including all of fundamental physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The only major exceptions are cases involving friction or when only the initial position and velocities are given.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Different action principles have different meaning for the variations; each specific application of an action principle requires a specific Lagrangian describing the physics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] A common name for any or all of these principles is "the principle of least action".
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For a discussion of the names and historical origin of these principles see action principle names.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] When total energy and the endpoints are fixed, Maupertuis's least action principle applies.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For example, to score points in basketball the ball must leave the shooters hand and go through the hoop, but the time of the flight is not constrained.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Some textbooks write (*δW*)*E* = 0 as Δ*S*0, to emphasize that the variation used in this form of the action principle differs from Hamilton's variation.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Here the total energy E is fixed during the variation, but not the time, the reverse of the constraints on Hamilton's principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Consequently, the same path and end points take different times and energies in the two forms.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The solutions in the case of this form of Maupertuis's principle are orbits: functions relating coordinates to each other in which time is simply an index or a parameter.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For time-invariant system, the action S relates simply to the abbreviated action W on the stationary path as $\Delta S=\Delta W-E\Delta t$ for energy E and time difference Δ*t* = *t*2 − *t*1.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] When the physics problem gives the two endpoints as a position and a time, that is as events, Hamilton's action principle applies.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For example, imagine planning a trip to the Moon.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] During your voyage the Moon will continue its orbit around the Earth: it is a moving target.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The Lagrangian $L=T-V$ is the difference between kinetic energy and potential energy at each point on the path.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Solution of the resulting equations gives the world line **q**(*t*).
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Starting with Hamilton's principle, the local differential Euler–Lagrange equation can be derived for systems of fixed energy.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action S in Hamilton's principle is the Legendre transformation of the action in Maupertuis's principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The concepts and many of the methods useful for particle mechanics also apply to continuous fields.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action integral runs over a Lagrangian density, but the concepts are so close that the density is often simply called the Lagrangian.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For quantum mechanics, the action principles have significant advantages: only one mechanical postulate is needed, if a covariant Lagrangian is used in the action, the result is relativistically correct, and they transition clearly to classical equivalents.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Both Richard Feynman and Julian Schwinger developed quantum action principles based on early work by Paul Dirac.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Feynman's integral method was not a variational principle but reduces to the classical least action principle; it led to his Feynman diagrams.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Schwinger's differential approach relates infinitesimal amplitude changes to infinitesimal action changes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] When quantum effects are important, new action principles are needed.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Instead of a single path with stationary action, all possible paths add (the integral over *xk*), weighted by a complex probability amplitude *e**iS*⁄*ħ*.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The phase of the amplitude is given by the action divided by the Planck constant or quantum of action: ⁠*S*/*ħ*⁠.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] When the action of a particle is much larger than ħ, ⁠*S*/*ħ*⁠ ≫ 1, the phase changes rapidly along the path: the amplitude averages to a small number.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Thus the Planck constant sets the boundary between classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] All of the paths contribute in the quantum action principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] At the end point, where the paths meet, the paths with similar phases add, and those with phases differing by π subtract.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Close to the path expected from classical physics, phases tend to align; the tendency is stronger for more massive objects that have larger values of action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In the classical limit, one path dominates – the path of stationary action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The Schwinger form makes analysis of variation of the Lagrangian itself, for example, variation in potential source strength, especially transparent.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] For every path, the action integral builds in value from zero at the starting point to its final value at the end.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Any nearby path has similar values at similar distances from the starting point.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Lines or surfaces of constant partial action value can be drawn across the paths, creating a wave-like view of the action.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Analysis like this connects particle-like rays of geometrical optics with the wavefronts of Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are applied to derive differential equations like the Euler–Lagrange equations or as direct applications to physical problems.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Action principles can be directly applied to many problems in classical mechanics, such as the shape of elastic rods under load, the shape of a liquid between two vertical plates (a capillary), or the motion of a pendulum when its support is in motion.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Quantum action principles are used in the quantum theory of atoms in molecules (QTAIM), a way of decomposing the computed electron density of molecules in to atoms as a way of gaining insight into chemical bonding.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Inspired by Einstein's work on general relativity, the renowned mathematician David Hilbert applied the principle of least action to derive the field equations of general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] contained a relativistically invariant volume element √−*g* *d*4*x* and the Ricci scalar curvature R.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The scale factor $\kappa$ is the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action principle is so central in modern physics and mathematics that it is widely applied including in thermodynamics, fluid mechanics, the theory of relativity, quantum mechanics, particle physics, and string theory.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] The action principle is preceded by earlier ideas in optics.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In ancient Greece, Euclid wrote in his *Catoptrica* that, for the path of light reflecting from a mirror, the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Hero of Alexandria later showed that this path has the shortest length and least time.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In 1915, David Hilbert applied the variational principle to derive Albert Einstein's equations of general relativity.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] In 1933, the physicist Paul Dirac demonstrated how this principle can be used in quantum calculations by discerning the quantum mechanical underpinning of the principle in the quantum interference of amplitudes.
[src:lagrangian-mechanics/principle-of-least-action] Subsequently Julian Schwinger and Richard Feynman independently applied this principle in quantum electrodynamics.
